<br>
To me, it's not about who can *get* agro, but managing the agro you cause. Taunt works to put you to the top of the Agro list. Warriors Taunt, so they can jump to the top. If the casters want to slow, DoT, snare etc, then perhaps they need to consider doing so before the Warrior engages the mob - while the mob is inbound. <br>
<br>
Indeed, if the puller is a Ranger, and the Ranger uses snare rather than just shooting with his bow, the casters can get their spells off while the Warrior moves forward and starts to taunt. Then, when all spells have landed, the Warrior takes the agro off the casters and starts slicing and dicing.<br>
<br>
You see, you don't have to build agro quickly. You only have to make sure you're at the top of the list. So the Rangers and the Paladins and who else goes into melee holds off on the stuns and agro grabbing spells and lets the Warrior - who has the greatest durability in combat - do his job.<br>
<br>
I learned this watching my warder taunt. <br>
<br>
I learned this as a Warrior who was always third fiddle to the Rangers and Paladins of the guild I was in. I learned it when the rangers and paladins fell over and I was the only melee left standing. I took the agro and I held it, and I took the beating the mob dished out and kept on going. Why? Because I had better Melee skills and more health than they.<br>
<br>
I learned this when, as a Cleric I saw a 57th warrior take agro off a 60th paladin without taunting. Both were just fighting, no spells being cast by them, the others, myself included, dropping the odd nuke in to speed up the take-down. And the warrior did not loose the agro until the Paladin stunned the mob.<br>
<br>
When you team with a warrior regularly, you learn how they fight, where their strengths are and where their weaknesses lie. They can taunt, and they taunt just fine. They can hold agro, even without proc'ing swords. They can stand there and take a beating, and, best of all, they can *be* a meat shield, can actually *defend* someone, and I don't know of another class who can.<br>
<br>
So, if you have a Warrior act as MA, work *with* them - don't compete or try to prove you *can* take agro from him. Just get on with the job and fight the enemy. It's that simple.<br>
<br>
But if you want to 'fix' things. If you want to say the warrior is broken and something needs doing about it, then how about simply setting Taunt to put the taunter to the top of the agro list, plus 1. So if the MA is taunting, each success will add another 'pip' to their standing on the list, so moving them up, not down. I just can't see that it's worth it. After all, it's the correct use of skills that make things more interesting. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=morgrist>Morgrist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 516<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/6/03 9:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4112.topic&index=92>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: *adds some coppers to the pot*</span><hr size=1> *tosses in a few platinum instead*<br>
 <br>
Truth be told, warriors have twofold problems here.<br>
 <br>
One is they can't generate hate as fast as most classes.<br>
 <br>
The second is they can't control that aggro and still maintain DPS to boot.<br>
 <br>
Raw aggro boosts aren't the key to this.<br>
 <br>
The problem is that the warrior,compared to literally everyone else is a one-trick pony.<br>
 <br>
As someone who's played a warrior in the dinosaur era of MMORPG's (Gemstone III, uber and legendary for my day and damn proud of it and Argent Aspis thank you) I can tell you this.<br>
 <br>
Warriors are given a pathetic array of options in EQ. None of their skills are truly weapons based,other than perhaps that a weapon is one-handed or two-handed. They have no way to truly focus their attacks in a &quot;burst&quot; effect like hybrids do,or perform any manner of feats as a melee type should.<br>
 <br>
They are forced into a singular twohanded plodding style, owing to their mono-dimensional role as &quot;defense tank&quot;. I cry bullshit. Warriors should be able to generate weapons-based effects the same way knights and paladins generate spell-based effects...in their case using the stamina bar rather than the mana one.<br>
 <br>
Face it. Does anyone here seriously give a damn if their little yellow bar slips to zero? It doesn't matter, yet it'd be the perfect measurement of a melee-type's special abilities.<br>
 <br>
Warriors should be able to exhaust themselves to perform the way that hybrids can,based on the weapons and styles they choose. SK's get weak PBAOE's. Our &quot;parent&quot; class should have sweeping rampage-style single strikes with their twohanders. Paladins generate potent stuns. Warriors should be able to rain interrupting bash-like jolts from their massive blunt weapons as well as from shield bashes. Knights can call up quick-cast DD's and massive single blasts. Warriors should be able to wind up for high-critical chance strikes or a mini-flurry of rapid blows, depending on the weapons at hand.<br>
 <br>
How to limit it? Stamina. No stamina, no special attacks. All it takes is nerfing STAMINA RECOVERY spells.<br>
 <br>
Can anyone here honestly tell me they'd care if zinging got nerfed if it meant warriors got to play with a better deck?<br>
<br>
And not as AA's. Nor disciplines. As skills the warrior learns and masters starting from the low levels and working their way up. A hybrid looks forward to their new spells on a regular basis. A warrior should be looking forward to their newest techinque or refinement therin. <br>
 <br>
And hey, just use the spell bar to set them up.<br>
 <br>
I think the idea of hybrid and warrior being related the way they are needs to stop. We are all melee types. We should all be capable of generating short term effects at a cost. Those abilities and their flavor should differ- SK's are necroish but definitely not &quot;necro lite&quot;. Paladins are not clerics with less spells and melee skills.<br>
 <br>
Warriors,as the third of the plate melee classes needs to be given abilities that allow the class to function properly. I think that method is making them a melee/stamina class,much the way SK and paladins are melee/mana classes.<br>
