<br>
Aggro is what makes it hard on warriors. Ideally, they are the best class to have taking damage since they have the best damage mitagation.<br>
<br>
The way I understand taunt working, it puts the warrior one point higher then everyone else on the hate list. One point can quickly be over ridden by just about anyone else. <br>
<br>
perhaps taunt needs to be changed. Perhaps taunt should move the warrior to the top of the list, and as they go up in level increase how much higher they placed. Rather then just one point, have it based on level, so a level 65 warrior when taunting would be placed at the top of the list by say 150 extra (just a random number) then everyone esle, to give them a buffer zone.<br>
<br>
Or, give warriors a new discipline that when used, will hold aggro no matter what, for a short time. Say 5 ticks when they first get it, and the time it lasts increases as they level. <br>
<br>
As it stands, since a warrior has the hardest time holding aggro, it's hard for anyone to want them for tanks. This seems out of balance to me, since the class best designed for taking damage, also has the hardest time keeping aggro. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lindonmaedhros>Lindon Maedhros</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/7/03 12:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4112.topic&index=95>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   My thoughts...</span><hr size=1> I have played a warrior to 59 (pre-luclin) and now a paladin to 65 here in FV.  My thoughts are...<br>
<br>
1 - Back in the Kunark/velious era paladins and SK were in much the same boat as warriors are now... for experience groups, there was simply no reason to take us over a similar level warrior.  Agro control was not as important as it is today, we did crappy DPS, and the utility of our spells were negated by the presence of our parent classes in a group.  Warriors were more efficient at taking damage, and much better at dealing it.  Warriors were far and away the best raid tanks.  This sparked a huge outcry from Knight players...<br>
<br>
2 - Following this outcry, we got some upgrades.  Paladins were given a line of fast-casting, low mana cost stuns (with short duration) starting at very low levels, some enhanced undead killing abilities, a new line of stackable buffs (brells), and a few more utility spells.  SK were boosted through additional DPS spells and taunting abilities.  During the later Velious and Luclin era, these abilities made us decent, but not &quot;uber&quot; classes.  Warriors continued to be the best raid tanks, but some balance had been achieved in XP groups.<br>
<br>
3 - With PoP, the mechanics of the game changed.  Paladins and SK did not gain any spectacular new abilities, but with the sudden appearence of &quot;XP grind&quot; mobs that hit for 600+, agro control became issue #1.  Warriors are still more efficient tanks, but slowing on the incoming became imperative, so a tank being able to grab snap agro was also imperative.  Enter those Knight abilities granted an expansion or two back, and suddenly SK and Paladins became more attractive tanks for XP groups than warriors.  As more Knights took on this role, we &quot;spoiled&quot; many of our groupmates -- wizards, mages, rangers, druids, etc... found they could go nuts on damage and rely on their Knights to chain cast to hold agro.  <br>
<br>
While still superior for healing efficiency, and better raid tanks, warriors fell into disfavor.  Itemization in PoP compounded the problem, because the really great taunting weapons were hard to come by, while good +hp armor for knights was fairly easy to aquire.<br>
<br>
4 - With LDoN, the softer hitting mobs have decreased the need for snap agro a bit, but this has been offset by the time limit.  Killing as quickly as possible is the norm, which means folks going nuts with the nukes again, which means trouble for warriors.<br>
<br>
As far as a solution to this situation, nefing knight agro is the worst thing to do.  It punishes everyone, and will radically alter the dynamics of single group hunts in places like PoP.  &quot;If I can't hold agro no one else should either&quot; just doesn't fly with me.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, warriors are clearly in need of an upgrade to their taunting ability.  My suggestion is a new AA for 59+ warriors that allows them to gain snap-agro at range, with a small recycle time (like 1 minute).  <br>
<br>
The danger with upgrading warriors is that it must be done in a way that doesn't trivialize raid encounters.  High end PoP bosses are dangerous in part because the entire raid has to be careful to keep it on the warrior.  Many of these mobs simply cannot be tanked by a knight.  If it becomes trivial for a warrior to hold their agro, it trivializes the raid.  So any upgrade has to be carefuly balanced between XP group and raid situations.<br>
<br>
The ideal is to find a balance somewhere between knights being superior at agro generation (our niche in groups) and warriors being superior at taking and dealing damage.  I do not think that balance currently exists in the 60+ game.  The solution needs to be some kind of ability earnable by all warriors, not some sort of itemization fix.  But the fix should not swing the pendulum too far back to the Kunark-era, where the only time SK and Paladins got groups was when no warrior of the appropriate level was available.<br>
